One of my passions is coding. Like language and music merging to create poetry, coding represents the junction of mathematics and logic. Modern programming languages are based around the computational model of "lambda calculus" invented by the mathematician Alonzo Church in the 1930s. While other mathematical computation systems have existed for a long time, lambda calculus continues to be unique in how fitting it is to the Computer Science ethos of building grand things from small, insignificant abstractions. Lambda calculus provides a simple set of rules for reducing and evaluating big, complicated algorithms that often are required to solve the important problems in programming. This simple, yet powerful model has been appealing to computer scientists for decades, and while smaller functional programming languages like Haskell are almost entirely based on lambda calculus, popular languages like Python borrow a great deal of semantics from it as well. However, there is another piece, logic, that takes away the intellectual isolation of pure conventional mathematics, and allows it to be applied to practical situations. Pure conventional mathematics lacks the infrastructure to support massive decision-trees, along with basic conditional features that underpin the basis of programming. However, with a logical framework such as the one built by George Boole, paired with Church's lambda calculus, coding gains the capacity to make sense of mathematical computations and gains the capability of decision-making beyond a mathematical foundation. For example, one could write an algorithm to calculate the cost of buying a house from information about mortgages, amortization, interest, location, etc., but simply being able to know this information is hardly useful. Logic allows you to dictate how to act based on the computations you perform. For this example, logic could be employed to help you determine if renting or buying is the most cost-effective solution when looking for a place to live. I love mathematics for the objective truth it can provide when given the correct information, along with how the same rules can be applied everywhere in an unchanging and definite way. For logic, I love it for many of the same reasons and appreciate how it has given us the ability to be better decision-makers. Specifically, I have had first-hand experience capitalizing on logic to develop compelling political arguments during Speech and Debate. In isolation, however, both logic and mathematic have characteristics I find lackluster. In mathematics, anything past 3rd-grade math seems to become less and less easy to apply meaningfully in the real-world. And the discussion and exploration of logic often appear to exist purely within the ivory tower. However, with advanced mathematics providing a clear foundation for complicated subjects like linear algebra that is integral in computer science and logic able to guide us in how to apply these mathematical computations, this intersection provided by computer science is invaluable. It is this intersection of mathematics and logic that makes coding appealing to me, combining the best parts of each while avoiding the worst.
